@Steven Rosmarin
Since "peakèd" is so obviously a past participle, it made wonder about the verb "to peak," as used such. There is one, which originally meant "to wander about," then "to mope" (which causes the wandering), then "to ail." Shakespeare used the phrase "peak and pine," as did many after him, just not me. There are also adjectives "peaky" and "peaking," which have been used in various dialects, at various times.

Thank you for giving me this petit frisson, as the puzzle certainly didn't

@Mean Old Lady
"What do you call it when a *verb-derived* word is used as a *modifying* adjective? Is it a "verbal adjective," or an "adjectival participle"?," he wondered, IRL
